; A2 double-derivation discriminator (promoted from the checkpoint-c notes'
; "Double-derivation repro"). Linear transitive closure over a @differential
; edge relation. The seed makes t(1,3) DOUBLE-derived: it has TWO independent
; supports -- the base rule edge(1,3), and the recursive rule
; t(1,2),edge(2,3). The batch then removes BOTH supports (retracts
; edge_msg(1,3) and edge_msg(2,3)); t(1,3) must OVERDELETE once per support
; and be fully retired (count 0), while t(1,2) -- whose sole support
; edge(1,2) is untouched -- must survive. Expected final t = {(1,2)}.
;
; This is the A2 seed-phase discriminator: a wrong derivation-counter seed
; (e.g. counting t(1,3) once instead of twice, or double-counting a single
; support) leaves t(1,3) either as a phantom survivor or a spurious under-
; flow. Its end state is checked against the positive-only equivalence
; oracle (goldens/tc_double_derive.oracle.stdout / .monotone.stdout).
#message edge_msg(u64 From, u64 To) @differential.

#local edge(From, To).
#local t(From, To).

#query t_out(free u64 From, free u64 To).

edge(From, To) : edge_msg(From, To).

t(From, To) : edge(From, To).
t(From, To) : t(From, X), edge(X, To).

t_out(From, To) : t(From, To).
